ology, anthropology, archeology, sociology, and history to examine the ways in which changing moral beliefs came to stigmatize forms of "socially sanctioned violence" such as human sacrifice, cannibalism, and slavery, eventually rendering them unacceptable. Could the same process work for war?Edited and with an introduction by political scientists Matthew Evangelista (Cornell University) and Neta C. Crawford (Boston University), both of whom worked with Forsberg.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPeacexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aViolencexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aWarxMoral and ethical aspects. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 70(DE-588)4033114-30(DE-627)1043600700(DE-576)209000309aKrieg2gnd 70(DE-588)4040222-80(DE-627)1045717800(DE-576)209038780aMoral2gnd 70(DE-588)4046588-30(DE-627)10619755X0(DE-576)209070153aPolitisches Verhalten2gnd 70(DE-588)4055903-80(DE-627)1061564540(DE-576)209115866aSozialverhalten2gnd 70(DE-588)4071465-20(DE-627)1043598890(DE-576)209184051aFriede2gnd 70(DE-588)4121849-80(DE-627)1057666150(DE-576)209546689aVerhaltensmuster2gnd 70(DE-588)4124385-70(DE-627)10574820X0(DE-576)209567619aVerbrechen gegen die Menschlichkeit2gnd 70(DE-588)4185105-50(DE-627)1052898840(DE-576)210030208aTheoriebildung2gnd 70(DE-588)4209283-80(DE-627)1043532010(DE-576)210191112aEinflussgröße2gnd 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh1 aCrawford, Neta C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEvangelista, Matthew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook pack